<subSubSection id="C373656FFFD1C8083EEEE42C6C099C2C" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD1C8083EEEE42C6F579B5F" blockId="5.[174,558,863,890]" box="[174,558,863,890]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">
<heading id="D09E8188FFD1C8083EEEE42C6F579B5F" box="[174,558,863,890]" fontSize="36" level="2" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="4C694D67FFD1C8083EEEE42C6F579B5F" authority="(Esper, [1787])" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Esper" baseAuthorityYear="1787" box="[174,558,863,890]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Catocala" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elocata">
<emphasis id="B91DEAF6FFD1C8083EEEE42C6C0E9B5F" bold="true" box="[174,375,863,890]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">Catocala elocata</emphasis>
(Esper, [1787])
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD1C8083EA3E4E36C099C2C" blockId="5.[174,1232,911,1257]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">
D e s c r i p t i o n. Egg subspherical, flattened (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083C9CE4FC6E5E9B8F" box="[732,807,911,938]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[174,207,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1233,184,1656]" captionTargetId="figure-5@7.[174,1233,184,1682]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 25–30. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 25–28 — Catocala elocata; 29, 30 — Catocala nupta. Scale bars: 25, 26, 29, 30 — 100 µm; 27, 28 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453450/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 25</figureCitation>
), height 
<quantity id="4C919B01FFD1C8083DCBE4FC696E9B8F" box="[907,1047,911,938]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" unit="mm" value="0.7" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.6">0.6–0.8 mm</quantity>
, diameter 
<quantity id="4C919B01FFD1C8083AD0E4FC6C6D9BEF" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="1.35" metricValueMin="1.25" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" unit="mm" value="1.3" valueMax="1.35" valueMin="1.25">1.25– 1.35 mm</quantity>
(n = 2). Chorion white, transparent. According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EFF84B15FFD1C8083D20E4DC697E9BEF" author="Doring, E." box="[864,1031,943,970]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" refId="ref3049" refString="Doring, E. Zur Morphologie der Schmetterlingseier. - Berlin: Akademie-Verlag, 1955. - 154 S." type="book" year="1955">Döring (1955)</bibRefCitation>
egg reddish-gray with broad purple stripe in middle part, which interrupted by white-yellow stripe. Micropylar area white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C373656FFFD1C8083EA3E37C6C8E9CCC" pageId="5" pageNumber="558" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BD636E4FFD1C8083EA3E37C6C8E9CCC" blockId="5.[174,1232,911,1257]" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">
Chorion ridged, marked on two thirds surface. Micropylar area clearly expressed, represented by rosette and 3 rows petalled cells (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083C86E35C6E6D9C6F" box="[710,788,1071,1098]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[174,207,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1233,184,1656]" captionTargetId="figure-5@7.[174,1233,184,1682]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 25–30. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 25–28 — Catocala elocata; 29, 30 — Catocala nupta. Scale bars: 25, 26, 29, 30 — 100 µm; 27, 28 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453450/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 26</figureCitation>
). Rosette with 9–10 petalled cells and 5 micropylar openings (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083F89E33C6F6E9C4F" box="[457,535,1103,1130]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[174,207,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1233,184,1656]" captionTargetId="figure-5@7.[174,1233,184,1682]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 25–30. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 25–28 — Catocala elocata; 29, 30 — Catocala nupta. Scale bars: 25, 26, 29, 30 — 100 µm; 27, 28 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453450/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 27</figureCitation>
). Cells of 1–2 series petalled and small. Tertiary cells large, broad, with pointed distal part (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083C5EE31C6F139CAF" box="[542,618,1135,1162]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[174,207,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1233,184,1656]" captionTargetId="figure-5@7.[174,1233,184,1682]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 25–30. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 25–28 — Catocala elocata; 29, 30 — Catocala nupta. Scale bars: 25, 26, 29, 30 — 100 µm; 27, 28 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453450/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 26</figureCitation>
). There are 16–19 of the 33–37 elevated, longitudinal ridges radiate from cells of micropylar area. Longest ridges slightly wavy, with comb. Walls of columnar cells slightly wavy and distinct as ridges. Aeropyles slightly expressed (
<figureCitation id="13522A61FFD1C8083A37E3DC69BA9CEF" box="[1143,1219,1199,1226]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[174,207,1728,1750]" captionTargetBox="[174,1233,184,1656]" captionTargetId="figure-5@7.[174,1233,184,1682]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 25–30. Eggs of Erebidae, Catocalinae: 25–28 — Catocala elocata; 29, 30 — Catocala nupta. Scale bars: 25, 26, 29, 30 — 100 µm; 27, 28 — 10 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453450" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453450/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="558">fig. 28</figureCitation>
). Chorion folded everywhere.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
